 To see whether our results are significant, we used permutation test with
 the statistic being 
\begin_inset Formula $s=mean(f(d))\ s.t\ (d<N)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the distance value, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(d)$
\end_inset

 is the correlation between pair of methylation sites and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=50$
\end_inset

 is the distance threshold given in nt.
 The reason we chose to use 
\begin_inset Formula $N=50$
\end_inset

 is because in several papers have demonstrated that two methylation sites
 which are less than 50nt apart, have high chance of being co-methylated
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $^{8,15}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{val}=\frac{\#(s_{i}\ge s)}{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is our number of permutations and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the statistic for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i'th$
\end_inset

 run.
 In our test, 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\#(s_{i}\ge s)=0$
\end_inset

 
\series default
which results in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{val}<\frac{1}{100000}$
\end_inset

.
 The null hypothesis is that there is no connection between physical distance
 and co-methylation.
 Our results suggest that we can reject the null hypothesis.
\end_layout

