\begin_layout Section
Highly Co-Methylated Sites Across Different Tissues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we wanted to analyze if sites that were highly co-methylated in one
 tissue are also highly co-methylated across other tissues.
 It has been shown that different tissues produce distinctive methylation
 patterns 
\series bold
(link)
\series default
, however, we wanted to examine if highly co-methylated sites preserve over
 different tissues despite that notion.
 Prior to this step, we chose to visualize if different tissues indeed exhibit
 different methylation signal.
 Note that we ran the same preprocessing steps described under the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preprocessing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 section before approaching this question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Principle Component Analysis (PCA)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first technique we chose to apply to our data is a linear dimensionality
 reduction named PCA.
 PCA is an unsupervised learning method which tries to preserve linear relations
hips in the data and is commonly used as a first step in analysis.
 Here we tried to see if PCA will be able to distinguish between tissues
 in all healthy tissues combined file:
\end_layout

